{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "ParticleScavengingCoeff",
        "description": "Below-cloud scavenging coefficient Λ_particle for an aerosol particle collected by monodisperse raindrops (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Chapter 20, Eq. 20.57): Λ_particle = (3/2)·E·p₀/D_p, where E is the Slinn (1983) raindrop-aerosol collision (collection) efficiency of Eqs. 20.53-20.54, p₀ the precipitation rate and D_p the raindrop diameter. E sums three collection mechanisms — Brownian diffusion, interception, and inertial impaction (switched on only when the Stokes number exceeds the critical Stokes number S*) — and is clamped to a maximum of 1; their competition produces the Greenfield gap, a scavenging minimum at accumulation-mode (~0.1-1 µm) particle sizes. Migrated from AtmosphericDeposition.jl@e4468c79 src/seinfeld_pandis_2006_ch20.jl:414 (`ParticleScavengingCoeff` @component). The upstream slinn_collection_efficiency helper and its diffusivity / relaxation-time / settling-velocity sub-helpers are decomposed into 18 named intermediate algebraic states (Re, D_diff, Sc, τ, St, S_star, E_diff, E_int, E_imp, ...) — identical to the sibling component particle_collection_eff.esm — and a 19th equation applies Eq. 20.57. The five raindrop/aerosol/thermodynamic inputs, the precipitation rate, and six physical constants are parameters; Re through E and Λ_particle are the algebraic outputs.",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_deposition",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "wet-scavenging",
            "below-cloud-scavenging",
            "ch20",
            "observed-only"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDeposition.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-n6u2)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed., Chapter 20: Wet Deposition, pp. 932-979. John Wiley & Sons, Inc. Eqs. 20.53-20.54 define the Slinn (1983) particle-drop collection efficiency; Eq. 20.57 the monodisperse-raindrop particle scavenging coefficient. ISBN 978-0-471-72018-8."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Slinn, W. G. N. (1983). Precipitation scavenging. In Atmospheric Sciences and Power Production (D. Randerson, ed.), Ch. 11, pp. 466-532. U.S. Department of Energy, DOE/TIC-27601. Original source of the semi-empirical collision-efficiency parameterization adopted as Eqs. 20.53-20.54 by Seinfeld & Pandis (2006)."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "ParticleScavengingCoeff": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDeposition.jl@e4468c79c8dd4aae88646cd16d6bcf290874742c:src/seinfeld_pandis_2006_ch20.jl:414\nUpstream `ParticleScavengingCoeff` is an MTK `@component` with six input `@parameters` (D_p, U_t, d_p, ρ_p, T, p₀) and two output `@variables` E(t) and Λ_particle(t), related by two algebraic equations: E ~ slinn_collection_efficiency(D_p, U_t, d_p, ρ_p, T) — the Slinn (1983) raindrop-aerosol collision (collection) efficiency, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Eqs. 20.53-20.54 — and Λ_particle ~ particle_scavenging_coeff(E, p₀, D_p), the monodisperse-raindrop scavenging coefficient Λ = (3/2)·E·p₀/D_p of Eq. 20.57. It returns `System(eqs, t, vars, params; name)` with no subsystems, so it is a flat algebraic model; the upstream `ParticleScavengingCoeff Component` test (test/seinfeld_pandis_2006_ch20_test.jl:284) checks equations(sys) == 2 and unknowns(sys) == 2.\n\nThe collection efficiency E is computed by the same module-level helper `slinn_collection_efficiency` used by the sibling component ParticleCollectionEfficiency. That helper's named local variables (Reynolds number, Schmidt number, relaxation time, Stokes number, the critical Stokes number S*, and the Brownian/interception/impaction efficiency terms) are migrated as 18 intermediate algebraic states — one equation each, in the helper's evaluation order, so every .esm equation maps to one source line — exactly as in components/atmospheric_deposition/sp06_ch20/particle_collection_eff.esm (esm-dbc5). The 18 slinn equations and their state variables here are identical to that sibling file. Inlining the helper into a single equation AST would instead duplicate the Re / Sc / St / stokes_diff subexpressions many times over (a several-hundred-node tree); after `mtkcompile` the 18 intermediates reduce to observed quantities and E is the same function of the five inputs as upstream. A 19th equation, Λ_particle = (3/2)·E·p₀/D_p (Eq. 20.57; the upstream `particle_scavenging_coeff` helper at src line 404), closes the component over its second output.\n\nThe three sub-helpers `particle_diffusivity` (Stokes-Einstein, src line 291), `particle_relaxation_time` (src line 269) and `particle_terminal_velocity` (src line 280) are inlined into the D_diff, τ and u_t_particle equations. The six module-level `@constants` (μ_air_sp, ρ_air_sp, μ_w_sp, ρ_w_sp, g_sp, kB_sp) migrate as fixed-default `type: parameter` entries holding their upstream numeric values (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006; μ_air from Table A.7), per the rig convention for MTK `@constants`. The upstream `cbrt(Sc)` cube root in the Brownian term is re-expressed as Sc^(1/3) with the `^` op (the spec §4.2 elementary-function set has no `cbrt`; Sc, a Schmidt number, is always strictly positive so the two are numerically equivalent). Julia's `pi` is inlined as the float64 literal 3.141592653589793, and the upstream `1//12`, `2//3` and `3//2` exact rationals are kept as integer-literal `/` nodes. The component has no `ifelse` nodes: the upstream final clamp ifelse(E_total > 1, 1, E_total) is migrated as min(1, E_total) — the identical upper clamp — and the upstream impaction term ifelse(stokes_diff <= 0, 0, safe_ratio*sqrt(safe_ratio)) is migrated as safe_ratio*sqrt(safe_ratio) directly, because safe_ratio = max(0, stokes_diff)/(max(0, stokes_diff) + 2/3) is already exactly 0 whenever stokes_diff <= 0, so both ifelse branches are bit-identical and the conditional is provably dead code. Eliding it keeps the model free of `Piecewise`, which avoids a sympy lambdify-printer path that substitutes every free symbol with 0 and trips on the resulting 0/0 NaN. The max(0, ·) in safe_ratio is retained — it keeps the sqrt argument non-negative, the upstream author's stated reason for the max. `system_kind` is left unset (zero differential states — no D operator).\n\nUpstream provides only structural and qualitative-bound tests for this component (the component test checks equations==2 / unknowns==2; the helper-level `Particle Scavenging Coefficient` test pins (3/2)·E·p₀/D_p ≈ 4.167e-5 at E=0.1). The inline `tests` here pin full-precision values: default_parameters uses the component defaults; aitken_mode_aerosol, accumulation_mode_aerosol and coarse_mode_aerosol reproduce the three particle-size regimes of the upstream `Slinn Collection Efficiency` test (D_p = 2e-3 m, U_t = 6.5 m/s, d_p in {1e-8, 1e-6, 1e-5} m) and confirm E_small > E_medium and the Greenfield-gap minimum; dense_coarse_aerosol exercises the sqrt(ρ_w/ρ_p) density correction; efficiency_clamp drives E_total > 1 so the Eq. 20.53 maximum-of-1 clamp fires (E pinned to 1.0); and heavy_precipitation raises p₀ tenfold, confirming E is independent of p₀ while Λ_particle scales linearly with it (Eq. 20.57). The E and slinn-intermediate expectations match the corresponding scenarios in particle_collection_eff.esm.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-6, abs=1e-12): observed-only algebraic system (no ODE integration). The 19 equations form a triangular chain of +, -, *, /, ^, sqrt, log, max and min on float64; round-off is ~1e-16 per op, so rel=1e-6 leaves ample headroom across the tested ranges (Re ~ 1e2, Sc ~ 1e5 to 3e7, E ~ 1e-4 to 1, Λ_particle ~ 1e-8 to 1e-3 s^-1). abs=1e-12 gates the exact-zero intermediates (safe_ratio, E_imp_unscaled, E_imp) in the no-impaction cases, where a pure relative tolerance would be degenerate."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-06,
                "abs": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "D_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.001,
                    "description": "Raindrop diameter"
                },
                "U_t": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 4.0,
                    "description": "Terminal velocity of the raindrop"
                },
                "d_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1e-06,
                    "description": "Aerosol particle diameter"
                },
                "ρ_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Aerosol particle density"
                },
                "T": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 298.0,
                    "description": "Temperature"
                },
                "p₀": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 2.778e-07,
                    "description": "Precipitation rate (1 mm/h = 2.778e-7 m/s)"
                },
                "μ_air_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/(m*s)",
                    "default": 1.72e-05,
                    "description": "Dynamic viscosity of air (Table A.7, Seinfeld & Pandis 2006)"
                },
                "ρ_air_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1.225,
                    "description": "Air density at standard conditions (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006)"
                },
                "μ_w_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/(m*s)",
                    "default": 0.001,
                    "description": "Dynamic viscosity of water"
                },
                "ρ_w_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Water density"
                },
                "g_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s^2",
                    "default": 9.81,
                    "description": "Gravitational acceleration"
                },
                "kB_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg*m^2/(s^2*K)",
                    "default": 1.3806488e-23,
                    "description": "Boltzmann constant"
                },
                "Re": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Raindrop Reynolds number based on drop radius, Re = D_p*U_t*ρ_air/(2*μ_air) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "D_diff": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^2/s",
                    "description": "Brownian diffusivity of the aerosol particle (Stokes-Einstein relation)"
                },
                "Sc": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Particle Schmidt number, Sc = μ_air/(ρ_air*D_diff) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "τ": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "s",
                    "description": "Particle relaxation time in the Stokes drag regime, τ = ρ_p*d_p^2/(18*μ_air)"
                },
                "u_t_particle": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "description": "Particle Stokes settling (terminal) velocity, u_t = τ*g"
                },
                "St": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Stokes number of the aerosol particle relative to the raindrop, St = 2*τ*(U_t - u_t)/D_p (dimensionless)"
                },
                "φ": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Aerosol-to-raindrop diameter ratio, φ = d_p/D_p (dimensionless)"
                },
                "ω": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Water-to-air dynamic viscosity ratio, ω = μ_w/μ_air (dimensionless)"
                },
                "S_star": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Critical Stokes number (Eq. 20.54) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_diff": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Brownian diffusion term of the collection efficiency (Eq. 20.53, first line) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_int": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Interception term of the collection efficiency (Eq. 20.53, second line) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "stokes_diff": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Stokes-number excess over the critical Stokes number, St - S* (dimensionless)"
                },
                "safe_ratio": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Clamped impaction ratio max(0, St-S*)/(max(0, St-S*) + 2/3) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "density_scaling": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Particle-density correction factor sqrt(ρ_w/ρ_p) for the impaction term (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_imp_unscaled": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Inertial impaction term before the density correction; zero when St ≤ S* (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_imp": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Inertial impaction term of the collection efficiency (Eq. 20.53, third line) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_total": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Sum of the three collection-efficiency terms before clamping (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Collection efficiency between a raindrop and an aerosol particle (Eq. 20.53), clamped to a maximum of 1 (dimensionless)"
                },
                "Λ_particle": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "description": "Below-cloud scavenging coefficient for an aerosol particle collected by monodisperse raindrops (Eq. 20.57)"
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "_comment": "Reynolds number based on drop radius (slinn_collection_efficiency, src line 310): Re = D_p*U_t*ρ_air/(2*μ_air)",
                    "lhs": "Re",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
